<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06205142 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06205142 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SEX; DISCRIMINATION; WOMEN; EMPLOYMENT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  WHEN San Jose author Beth Milwid inter-; viewed professional women for herbook, &quot;Working With Men,&quot; she asked them to give advice to women coming upthrough the ranks. Here is a sampling of their suggestions:  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Living  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  WORKPLACE SURVIVORS OFFER ADVICE  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  See also related story on this page.  </MEMO><TEXT>  (box)&quot;The tendency is to think it's all been done, that women are nowaccepted. If women assume that working is a God-given right, they will fall 10steps back.&quot;;    (box)&quot;Figure out how the pecking order works and what thenorms of the organization are. They're going to be male norms, most likely,and we women need to know what that culture is early on.&quot;; (box)&quot;You want toknow what I do to get men to take me seriously? I overwhelm them with myknowledge.&quot;; (box)&quot;A woman must do her homework, and once she's done it, shemust be sure to speak up. And she must be 100 percent sure of what she'stalking about.&quot;; (box)&quot;Take it on faith that the first five years are very,very difficult, that the first one is particularly hard and that your firstjob will probably not be the ultimate job.&quot;; (box)&quot;If you're excludedinformally, it will hurt you. People may respect other people for theirprofessional purposes, but they also like to work with people they feelcomfortable around.&quot;; (box)&quot;Be good-natured but also be sort of curt. You haveto be somewhat shut down and let little sexual innuendoes slide right off yourback.&quot;; (box)&quot;I've heard many young women say, 'But they never give me thereal stuff to do.' And I say, 'That's right. They never do. You have to askfor it.' &quot;; (box)&quot;Believe that the top is accessible, because unless youbelieve it, it won't ever be.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  -- Michalene Busico  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910723  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  291  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday July 23, 199100205142,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>